# PHASE 1 — Security & Governance Guardrails

## 1.1 Objective

Ensure every Bessie output is traceable to approved source data, every calculation is performed by deterministic code (never the LLM), and every interaction is logged. Build the minimum governance layer required before Bessie's output can be trusted in a production context.

## 1.2 Governance Framework

### Principle 1 — AI Explains, Code Calculates

**The single most important rule.** Claude should never compute a financial figure — it should only interpret figures that Tool 6 (deterministic code) has already computed.

| Do | Don't |
|---|---|
| "GL 90010 shows NOI of $6.15M (from Yardi actuals Jul–Mar)" | "I estimate NOI is approximately $6M" |
| "Baseline forecast uses trailing 3-month average per methodology" | "I think revenue will be around $1.1M/month" |
| "Vacancy improved 10% vs trailing avg per system prompt rule" | "Vacancy looks about 10% better than usual" |

**Enforcement mechanism:** The system prompt explicitly prohibits Bessie from performing math or estimating quantities not present in Tool 6's `keyFindings` output. The QA Review Agent (Phase 3) checks for unsupported numeric claims.

### Principle 2 — Source Attribution on Every Number

Every figure in Bessie's response must be traceable to one of:
- A GL code in a Yardi actuals file
- A computed field in `keyFindings` from Tool 6
- A rule in the RAG knowledge base (Phase 2)
- A documented assumption in the system prompt

Figures without clear attribution are flagged as a QA failure in Phase 3.

### Principle 3 — Deterministic First, AI Second

The processing chain enforces this order:
1. Tool 6 runs deterministic code (no LLM involved)
2. Review Agent runs deterministic validation checks (no LLM)
3. LLM commentary is generated ONLY after Steps 1 and 2 pass
4. LLM receives pre-validated numbers — it cannot alter them

## 1.3 Implementation Components

### A. Telegram User ID Whitelist (Highest Priority)

Currently Bessie has no authentication. Any Telegram user who knows the chat URL can invoke it.

**Implementation:**
- In the Chat Trigger node (or an early Code node), check the incoming user ID against an approved list
- Store the whitelist in an n8n environment variable or a Google Sheet (Google Sheet preferred — allows non-developer updates)

```javascript
// Code node: Authenticate User (runs before AI Agent)
const ALLOWED_USERS = (process.env.BESSIE_ALLOWED_USERS || '').split(',').map(s => s.trim());
const userId = $input.first().json.userId || $input.first().json.chatId || '';

if (ALLOWED_USERS.length > 0 && !ALLOWED_USERS.includes(String(userId))) {
  return [{ json: {
    blocked: true,
    message: `Access denied. User ID ${userId} is not authorized. Contact your system administrator.`
  }}];
}
return [{ json: { blocked: false, userId } }];
```

- Add an IF node after this: if `blocked === true`, return the denial message without passing to AI Agent
- Add authorized user IDs to `BESSIE_ALLOWED_USERS` env var (comma-separated) in Hostinger Docker Manager

### B. Input Sanitization

Prevent prompt injection and malformed requests before they reach the LLM.

```javascript
// Code node: Sanitize Input
const raw = $input.first().json.chatInput || '';

const issues = [];

// Block prompt injection patterns
const injectionPatterns = [
  /ignore (previous|all|above) instructions/i,
  /system prompt/i,
  /you are now/i,
  /pretend (you are|to be)/i,
  /jailbreak/i,
  /DAN mode/i,
];
for (const p of injectionPatterns) {
  if (p.test(raw)) issues.push('Potential prompt injection detected');
}

// Block excessively long inputs (>2000 chars is unusual for a forecast request)
if (raw.length > 2000) issues.push('Input exceeds 2000 character limit');

if (issues.length > 0) {
  return [{ json: {
    blocked: true,
    message: `Your request could not be processed: ${issues.join('; ')}. Please rephrase and try again.`
  }}];
}
return [{ json: { blocked: false, sanitizedInput: raw.trim() } }];
```

### C. Tool 6 Output Schema Validation

Before Bessie receives Tool 6's output and writes a response, validate the schema to catch corrupt or incomplete computation results.

```javascript
// Code node: Validate Tool 6 Output (runs inside Tool 6 Format Output, or as a separate pre-delivery check)
const result = JSON.parse($input.first().json.output || '{}');

const errors = [];

if (!result.success) errors.push('Tool 6 reported failure: ' + (result.message || 'unknown'));
if (!result.keyFindings) errors.push('Missing keyFindings');
if (result.keyFindings) {
  if (typeof result.keyFindings.ytdRevenue !== 'number') errors.push('ytdRevenue is not a number');
  if (typeof result.keyFindings.ytdNOI !== 'number') errors.push('ytdNOI is not a number');
  if (result.keyFindings.ytdNOIMargin < -1 || result.keyFindings.ytdNOIMargin > 1)
    errors.push(`NOI margin ${result.keyFindings.ytdNOIMargin} is outside plausible range [-1, 1]`);
  if (!result.keyFindings.fullYearRevenueBaseline)
    errors.push('Missing fullYearRevenueBaseline');
}
if (!result.fileName) errors.push('Missing fileName');
if (!result.driveLink) errors.push('Missing driveLink');

if (errors.length > 0) {
  return [{ json: {
    valid: false,
    errors,
    message: `Forecast output failed validation: ${errors.join('; ')}`
  }}];
}
return [{ json: { valid: true, ...result } }];
```

