# Risks, Trade-Offs & Best Practices

## Phase 1 Risks

| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |
|---|---|---|---|
| Whitelist env var too strict — locks out legitimate users | Medium | Medium | Keep whitelist in Google Sheet for easy non-developer updates |
| Schema validation too strict — blocks valid edge-case outputs | Low | High | Log validation failures for first 2 weeks before hard-blocking |
| Audit log Google Sheet hits row limit (10M rows) | Very Low | Low | Archive annually to new sheet |

## Phase 2 Risks

| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |
|---|---|---|---|
| Knowledge docs are stale/wrong — RAG makes Bessie more confidently wrong | Medium | High | Quarterly review cycle; every doc has `last_reviewed` date; flag docs > 6 months old |
| Retrieval returns irrelevant chunks — context pollution | Medium | Medium | Filter by `applicable_properties` and `status=active`; tune relevance threshold |
| OpenAI embedding cost spikes | Low | Low | text-embedding-3-small is ~$0.002 per full re-ingest of 50 docs; negligible |
| Qdrant Cloud free tier insufficient | Low | Low | Free tier supports 1GB / 1M vectors; easily sufficient for years |

## Phase 3 Risks

| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |
|---|---|---|---|
| Retry loop causes runaway costs | Low | Medium | Hard cap: max 2 retries per run; retry logged to audit sheet |
| LLM Review Agent hallucinates false positives | Medium | Medium | Narrow structured questions reduce surface area; Tier 1 deterministic checks carry more weight |
| Confidence threshold too high — too many escalations | Medium | Low | Start at 0.75 threshold, tune upward after 20+ production runs |

## Best Practices Summary

1. **Build Phase 1 before any real-property forecasts.** Governance is not optional for financial data.
2. **Start RAG with 5 high-quality documents, not 50 mediocre ones.** Quality of knowledge matters more than quantity.
3. **The QA agent's Tier 1 checks are the most valuable thing in Phase 3.** Even without the LLM review layer, deterministic math checks alone prevent the most damaging failures.
4. **Version everything.** System prompts, knowledge docs, n8n workflows — all in GitHub with commit messages explaining why a change was made.
5. **Never trust a confidence score you haven't tested.** Run the QA agent against 10 known-good and 5 known-bad outputs before deploying to production.

